# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engine-block
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engine-block/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:engine-block/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:engine-block/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:engine-block/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:engine-block/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:engine-block/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:engine-block/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:engine-block/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:engine-block/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:engine-block/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:engine-block/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:engine-block/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:engine-block/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:engine-block/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:engine-block/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] An **aluminium alloy** (UK/IUPAC) or **aluminum alloy** (NA; see spelling differences) is an alloy in which aluminium (Al) is the predominant metal.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The typical alloying elements are copper, magnesium, manganese, silicon, tin, nickel and zinc.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] There are two principal classifications, namely casting alloys and wrought alloys, both of which are further subdivided into the categories heat-treatable and non-heat-treatable.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] About 85% of aluminium is used for wrought products, for example rolled plate, foils and extrusions.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Cast aluminium alloys yield cost-effective products due to their low melting points, although they generally have lower tensile strengths than wrought alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The most important cast aluminium alloy system is Al–Si, where the high levels of silicon (4–13%) contribute to give good casting characteristics.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are widely used in engineering structures and components where light weight or corrosion resistance is required.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Alloys composed mostly of aluminium have been very important in aerospace manufacturing since the introduction of metal-skinned aircraft.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium–magnesium alloys are both lighter than other aluminium alloys and much less flammable than other alloys that contain a very high percentage of magnesium.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloy surfaces will develop a white, protective layer of aluminium oxide when left unprotected by anodizing or correct painting procedures.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] In a wet environment, galvanic corrosion can occur when an aluminium alloy is placed in electrical contact with other metals with more positive corrosion potentials than aluminium, and an electrolyte is present that allows ion exchange.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Also referred to as dissimilar-metal corrosion, this process can occur as exfoliation or as intergranular corrosion.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys can be improperly heat-treated, causing internal element separation which corrodes the metal from the inside out.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloy compositions are registered with The Aluminum Association.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Many organizations publish more specific standards for the manufacture of aluminium alloys, including the SAE International standards organization, specifically its aerospace standards subgroups, and ASTM International.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys with a wide range of properties are used in engineering structures.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Alloy systems are classified by a number system (ANSI) or by names indicating their main alloying constituents (DIN and ISO).
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Selecting the right alloy for a given application entails considerations of its tensile strength, density, ductility, formability, workability, weldability, and corrosion resistance, to name a few.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] A brief historical overview of alloys and manufacturing technologies is given in.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are used extensively in aircraft due to their high strength-to-weight ratio.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Pure aluminium is much too soft for such uses, and it does not have the high tensile strength that is needed for building airplanes and helicopters.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys typically have elastic moduli of about 70 GPa, which is about one-third of the elastic modulus of steel alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Therefore, for a given load, a component or unit made of an aluminium alloy will experience a greater deformation in the elastic regime than a steel part of identical size and shape.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] With completely new metal products, the design choices are often governed by the choice of manufacturing technology.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Extrusions are particularly important in this regard, owing to the ease with which aluminium alloys, particularly the Al-Mg-Si series, can be extruded to form complex profiles.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] In general, stiffer and lighter designs can be achieved with aluminium alloys than is feasible with steels.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] For instance, consider the bending of a thin-walled tube: the second moment of area is inversely related to the stress in the tube wall; that is, stresses are lower for larger values.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The second moment of area is proportional to the cube of the radius times the wall thickness, so increasing the radius (and weight) by 26% will lead to a halving of the wall stress.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] For this reason, bicycle frames made of aluminium alloys make use of larger tube diameters than steel or titanium in order to yield the desired stiffness and strength.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] In automotive engineering, cars made of aluminium alloys employ space frames made of extruded profiles to ensure rigidity.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] This represents a radical change from the common approach for current steel car design, which depend on the body shells for stiffness, known as unibody design.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are widely used in automotive engines, particularly in engine blocks and crankcases due to the weight savings that are possible.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Since aluminium alloys are susceptible to warping at elevated temperatures, the cooling system of such an engine is critical.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Manufacturing techniques and metallurgical advancements have also been instrumental for successful applications in automotive engines.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] In the 1960s, the aluminium cylinder heads of the Chevrolet Corvair earned a reputation for failure and stripping of threads, which is not seen in current aluminium cylinder heads.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] An important structural limitation of aluminium alloys is their lower fatigue strength compared to steel.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] In controlled laboratory conditions, steels display a fatigue limit, which is the stress amplitude below which no failures occur – the metal does not continue to weaken with extended stress cycles.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys do not have this lower fatigue limit and will continue to weaken with continued stress cycles.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys are therefore sparsely used in parts that require high fatigue strength in the high-cycle regime (more than 107 stress cycles).
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Often, the metal's sensitivity to heat must also be considered.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Even a relatively routine workshop procedure involving heating is complicated by the fact that aluminium, unlike steel, will melt without first glowing red.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Forming operations where a blow torch is used can reverse or remove the effects of heat treatment.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] No visual signs reveal how the material is internally damaged.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Much like welding heat-treated, high-strength link chain, all strength is now lost by heat of the torch.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The chain is dangerous and must be discarded.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium is subject to internal stresses and strains.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Sometimes years later, improperly welded aluminium bicycle frames may gradually twist out of alignment from the stresses of the welding process.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Thus, the aerospace industry avoids heat altogether by joining parts with rivets of like-metal composition, other fasteners, or adhesives.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Stresses in overheated aluminium can be relieved by heat-treating the part in an oven and gradually cooling it—in effect annealing the stresses.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Yet these parts may still become distorted, so that heat-treating of welded bicycle frames, for instance, can result in a significant fraction becoming misaligned.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] If the misalignment is not too severe, the cooled parts may be bent into alignment.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] If the frame is properly designed for rigidity (see above), that bending will require enormous force.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium's intolerance of high temperatures has not precluded its use in rocketry, even for use in constructing combustion chambers where gases can reach 3500 K.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Because of its high conductivity and relatively low price compared with copper in the 1960s, aluminium was introduced at that time for household electrical wiring in North America, even though many fixtures had not been designed to accept aluminium wire.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] All of this resulted in overheated and loose connections, and this in turn resulted in some fires.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Builders then became wary of using the wire, and many jurisdictions outlawed its use in very small sizes, in new construction.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Yet newer fixtures were eventually introduced with connections designed to avoid loosening and overheating.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] At first they were marked "Al/Cu", but they now bear a "CO/ALR" coding.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Another way to forestall the heating problem is to crimp the short "pigtail" of copper wire.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] A properly done high-pressure crimp by the proper tool is tight enough to reduce any thermal expansion of the aluminium.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Today, new alloys, designs, and methods are used for aluminium wiring in combination with aluminium terminations.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Wrought and cast aluminium alloys use different identification systems.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Wrought aluminium is identified with a four-digit number which identifies the alloying elements.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Cast aluminium alloys use a four-to-five-digit number with a decimal point.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The digit in the hundreds place indicates the alloying elements, while the digit after the decimal point indicates the form (cast shape or ingot).
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The temper designation follows the cast or wrought designation number with a dash, a letter, and potentially a one-to-three-digit number, e.g.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Note: -W is a relatively soft intermediary designation that applies after heat treat and before aging is completed.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The -W condition can be extended at extremely low temperatures but not indefinitely and depending on the material will typically last no longer than 15 minutes at ambient temperatures.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The International Alloy Designation System is the most widely accepted naming scheme for wrought alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Each alloy is given a four-digit number, where the first digit indicates the major alloying elements, the second—if different from 0—indicates a variation of the alloy, and the third and fourth digits identify the specific alloy in the series.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] For example, in alloy 3105, the number 3 indicates the alloy is in the manganese series, 1 indicates the first modification of alloy 3005, and finally 05 identifies it in the 3000 series.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 1000 series are essentially pure aluminium with a minimum 99% aluminium content by weight and can be work hardened.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 2000 series alloys are alloyed with copper and can be precipitation hardened to strengths comparable to steel.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Formerly referred to as duralumin, they were once the most common aerospace alloys, but were susceptible to stress corrosion cracking and are increasingly replaced by 7000 series alloys in new designs.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 3000 series alloys are alloyed with manganese, and can be work hardened.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 4000 series alloys are alloyed with silicon.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Variations of aluminium–silicon alloys intended for casting (and therefore not included in 4000 series) are also known as silumin.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 5000 series alloys are alloyed with magnesium, and offer superb corrosion resistance, making them suitable for marine applications.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 5083 alloy has the highest strength of non-heat-treated alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Most 5000 series alloys include manganese as well.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 6000 series alloys are alloyed with magnesium and silicon.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] They are easy to machine, are weldable, and can be precipitation hardened, but not to the high strengths that 2000 and 7000 can reach.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 6061 alloy is one of the most commonly used general-purpose aluminium alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 7000 series alloys are alloyed with zinc, and can be precipitation hardened to the highest strengths of any aluminium alloy.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Most 7000 series alloys include magnesium and copper as well.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 8000 series alloys are alloyed with other elements which are not covered by other series.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium–lithium alloys are an example.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Manganese plus chromium must be between 0.12 and 0.50%.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] This limit applies to all elements for which no other limit is specified on a given row, because no column exists or because the column is blank.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The Aluminum Association (AA) has adopted a nomenclature similar to that of wrought alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] British Standard and DIN have different designations.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] In the AA system, the second two digits reveal the minimum percentage of aluminium; for example, 150.x corresponds to a minimum of 99.50% aluminium.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The digit after the decimal point takes a value of 0 or 1, denoting casting and ingot respectively.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Titanium alloys, which are stronger but heavier than Al-Sc alloys, are still much more widely used.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The main application of metallic scandium by weight is in aluminium–scandium alloys for minor aerospace industry components.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] These alloys contain between 0.1% and 0.5% (by weight) of scandium.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] They were used in the Russian military aircraft MiG-21 and MiG-29.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Some items of sports equipment, which rely on high-performance materials, have been made with scandium–aluminium alloys, including baseball bats, lacrosse sticks, bicycle frames and components, and tent poles.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] U.S. gunmaker Smith & Wesson produces revolvers with frames composed of scandium alloy and cylinders of titanium.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Due to its light weight and high strength, aluminium alloys are desired materials to be applied in spacecraft, satellites, and other components to be deployed in space.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] However, this application is limited by the energetic particle irradiation emitted by the Sun.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The impact and deposition of solar energetic particles within the microstructure of conventional aluminium alloys can induce the dissolution of most common hardening phases, leading to softening.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The recently introduced crossover aluminium alloys are being tested as surrogates to 6xxx and 7xxx series alloys in environments where energetic particle irradiation is a major concern.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Such crossover aluminium alloys can be hardened via precipitation of a chemical complex phase known as T-phase in which the radiation resistance has been proved to be superior than other hardening phases of conventional aluminium alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The terms **aircraft aluminium** or **aerospace aluminium** usually refers to 7075.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 4047 aluminium is a unique alloy used in aerospace and automotive applications as a cladding alloy or filler material.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] As filler, aluminium alloy 4047 strips can be combined to intricate applications to bond two metals.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 6951 is a heat-treatable alloy providing additional strength to the fins while increasing sag resistance; this allows the manufacturer to reduce the gauge of the sheet and therefore reducing the weight of the formed fin.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] These distinctive features make aluminium alloy 6951 one of the preferred alloys for heat transfer and heat exchangers manufactured for aerospace applications.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 6063 aluminium alloys are heat-treatable with moderately high strength, excellent corrosion resistance, and good extrudability.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] They are regularly used as architectural and structural members.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] These alloys are used for boat building and shipbuilding, and other marine and salt-water sensitive shore applications.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 4043, 5183, 6005A, and 6082 also used in marine constructions and off shore applications.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 6111 aluminium and 2008 aluminium are extensively used for external automotive body panels, with 5083 and 5754 used for inner body panels.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Bonnets have been manufactured from 2036, 6016, and 6111 alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Truck and trailer body panels have used 5456 aluminium.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Automobile frames often use 5182 aluminium or 5754 aluminium formed sheets, 6061 or 6063 extrusions.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Wheels have been cast from A356.0 aluminium or formed 5xxx sheet.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Engine blocks and crankcases are often cast from aluminium alloys.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] The most popular aluminium alloys used for cylinder blocks are A356, 319, and to a minor extent 242.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloys containing cerium are being developed and implemented in high-temperature automotive applications, such as cylinder heads and turbochargers, and in other energy-generation applications.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] These alloys were initially developed as a way to increase the usage of cerium, which is over-produced in rare-earth mining operations for more coveted elements such as neodymium and dysprosium, but gained attention for their strength at high temperatures over long periods of time.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] They gain strength from the presence of an Al11Ce3 intermetallic phase which is stable up to temperatures of 540 °C, and retains its strength up to 300 °C, making it quite viable at elevated temperatures.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Aluminium–cerium alloys are typically cast, due to their excellent casting properties, although work has also been done to show that laser-based additive manufacturing techniques can be used as well to create parts with more complex geometries and greater mechanical properties.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] Recent work has largely focused on adding higher-order alloying elements to the binary Al-Ce system to improve its mechanical performance at room and elevated temperatures, such as iron, nickel, magnesium, or copper, and work is being done to understand the alloying element interactions further.
[src:engine-block/aluminium-alloy] 6061 aluminium and 6351 aluminium are widely used in breathing gas cylinders for scuba diving and SCBA alloys.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A **replacement automobile engine** is an engine or a major part of one that is sold alone, without the other parts required to make a functional car (for example a drivetrain).
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] These engines are produced either as aftermarket parts or as reproductions of an engine that has gone out of production.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Replacement engines are used to replace classic car engines that are in poor condition or broken, or to install a more powerful or more fuel efficient engine in a vehicle.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Replacement engines are often used to make old cars more reliable for daily driving.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Classic car hobbyists may also install reproductions of a rare powerplant in a classic car (this is most often seen in Mopar muscle cars that have the 426 Hemi installed into them).
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Aftermarket engines are used in many forms of motorsport.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Some late model racecar series use "crate engines" many of which are made by independent firms.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] This ensures that drivers all have similarly powered racecars.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Legends and Allison Legacy Series cars also use sealed crate motors.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A **short block** is an engine sub-assembly comprising the portion of the cylinder block below the head gasket but above the oil pan, which usually includes the assembled engine block, crankshaft, connecting rods, and pistons with piston rings properly installed.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] An in-block cam engine short block includes the camshaft, timing gear, and any balance shafts.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Overhead cam engines don't include those parts.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Short block engines became popular after World War II, when mass production led to great consistency between individual engines; before then, most engines were hand-built and had idiosyncratic variations.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Short blocks became less popular after the 1970s when overhead camshaft (OHC) engines became the norm, as the rational unit of replacement was the long block, which includes the head, camshaft and valve gear.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A short block is the preferred replacement component for a worn-out engine that requires major servicing beyond the capabilities of a local repair garage, when instead a machine shop may be needed.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The short block represents the major wear items of an engine: piston rings, and potentially a rebore of the cylinder bores or replacement liners, together with reground bearings on the crankshaft.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Although replacing the rings or bearing shells was at one time considered typical garage work, the need for a boring or crank grinding machine now exceed the capabilities of a standard automotive repair garage.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A short block includes the preassembled set of major parts needed that generally exceed the capability of the garage, in one item.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The third item sometimes requiring machining, the re-cutting of valve seats in the cylinder head, was less frequently needed.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Grinding of valves to fit was once a regular garage task, as was light re-cutting with hand tools, when cast iron seats were common.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Once steel seat inserts came into use, either as a result of the switch to unleaded petrol in the 1970s or fitted into high-performance aluminium heads, machining of heads and the replacement of seats became equally commonly required.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Aluminium cylinder heads could also be damaged by warping after overheating, often requiring machining to re-flatten them.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A short block has advantages over dismantling the engine and sending the crankshaft and other related automotive parts away for rework.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It is usually quicker to obtain, requiring only a single shipment, rather than having to ship parts to and from the machine shop and the interim time spent at the shop to re-machine those parts.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The short block would also have been built in a workshop that was hopefully cleaner and more organised for the specialism of engine building.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Sidevalves were pre-eminent before the short block appeared as a common item, and they also offered little saving by omitting the (simple) head.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A **long block** is an engine sub-assembly that consists of the assembled short block with crankshaft, cylinder head, camshaft (usually), and valve train.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A long block does not include the fuel system, electrical, intake, and exhaust components, as well as other components.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A long block may include the balancer/damper, timing cover, oil pan and valve covers.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] A long block engine replacement typically requires swapping out parts from the original engine to the long block.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] These parts can include the oil pan, timing cover, valve covers, intake manifold, emission-control parts, carburetor or fuel injection system, the exhaust manifold(s), alternator, starter, power steering pump (if any), and air conditioner compressor (if any).
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Technically, a "crate engine" or "crate motor" is any automobile engine that is shipped to the installer in a crate, which can include short or long block configurations.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] For this article, a crate engine is defined as a fully-assembled engine that includes more than what is typically installed on a long block; the exact configuration will vary by vendor.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It is also sometimes known as a "deluxe long block", which usually includes the fuel and intake system, distributor, oil pan, and ignition system.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In some cases, exhaust manifold(s) and the water pump are included.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are manufactured by many different companies, but they all share the same characteristics of being complete engines nearly ready to install once removed from the crate.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Generally a crate engine still will require additional parts to be fitted, which can range from minor (engine oil dipstick) to major (intake manifold and fuel injection system), depending on the engine package purchased and the targeted vehicle application.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] This type of engine has various applications including general replacement, hot rod builds, and motorsports competition.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are often seen as an economical and more reliable solution as opposed to engine overhauls or custom builds.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Such engines are built by specialist engine builders, working in clean and well-equipped workshops, rather than general purpose repair garages.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines may be either brand new, or substantially rebuilt.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] If rebuilt, they will have been rebuilt to an extent such that they are considered to be of equal quality, reliability and expected lifetime as a new engine.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are well suited in many different vehicle platforms.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are often seen as an economical choice no matter what the application is.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In general automobile engine replacement, a crate engine is often very competitively priced when compared to the cost of a full rebuild of a faulty engine.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It is also quicker to ship from stock than to wait an equal time for parts, then to begin a rebuild.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Installers often opt for the crate engine because of the cost and ease of replacement.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are typically a bolt-in replacement with no internal work being performed to the engine compared to a complete overhaul that requires internal part replacement by trained mechanics.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Hot Rod and other custom street applications also often choose a crate engine because of the higher value when compared to a custom built engine.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In motorsports, the crate engine option has become very popular for various reasons.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are often a more affordable option when compared to a purpose-built race engine so budget racers often go this route.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The crate engine also has developed a large fan base in many different racing series because of the competitive racing.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] As all racers in the field have identical engines, the races are won by driver's talent and chassis setup, and not the amount of horsepower a team can afford to build into their engine.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In general, simply swapping an internal combustion engine for an electric traction motor is not sufficient; a complete electric vehicle (EV) drivetrain conversion also requires installation of a storage battery, inverter, reduction gear, and controller.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Most of these separate components can be packaged with the motor in a unit that is dimensionally compatible with the existing engine compartment, but the battery is usually the bulkiest, heaviest component of an EV powertrain and can create a significant challenge for fitment.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In recent years, the restoration and EV conversion of a classic car has become known as an *electromod*, a portmanteau of electrification and restomod.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Hobbyists have been converting cars to EVs since at least the 1960s.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Many recent non-factory electromods are implemented by extracting and adapting the complete drivetrain (traction motor(s), battery, controller, and inverter) from an existing mass-produced EV, such as Tesla.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] East Coast Defender demonstrated a Tesla EV-sourced powertrain conversion of a 1969–96 Range Rover Classic, developed with Electric Classic Cars, to *Motor Trend* in 2021.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In October 2019 there were no purpose-built crate engine EV kits available commercially, but such projects were in development.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] For example, EV West announced their Revolt Tesla Crate Motor in 2020, which married an electric traction motor from Tesla with a gear reduction unit and ended in a universal joint yoke, a suitable interface for a driveshaft.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Mechanically, the motor is fitted with mounts compatible with Chevrolet small-block engines to take advantage of numerous small-block repower kits.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Previously in 2018, Chevrolet Performance advanced an "electric crate motor" concept with the unveiling of the eCOPO Camaro at that year's SEMA show.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The eCOPO Camaro was a 2019 COPO Camaro which was equipped with a pair of BorgWarner HVH250-150 motor assemblies instead of the conventional piston engine.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The electric traction motor essentially served as a drop-in replacement with the same bellhousing bolt pattern and crankshaft flange as the LS engine family, so the car retained the same transmission, driveshaft, and axles as the conventional COPO Camaro.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] At the 2019 SEMA show, Chevrolet continued to develop the concept, following up with the E-10 Concept, which used the powertrains from two Bolts repackaged into in a restored 1962 C-10 pickup truck.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The following year for SEMA, Chevrolet showcased the "Electric Connect and Cruise" eCrate package in October 2020, which included the main drivetrain components of a single Bolt (motor, battery, controller, and inverter), and was demonstrated as a retrofit to a restored 1977 K5 Blazer.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The kit was scheduled to go on sale in the second half of 2021.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The Bolt motor is modified by removing the differential and reduction gear unit, then fitting an adapter plate and crank flange, allowing it to bolt to a conventional transmission.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Together with the controller and inverter, the motor occupies approximately the same space as a small-block V8; the 900 lb (410 kg) battery presents a greater challenge for packaging, which is why the initial development has focused on trucks.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] As of July 2022, it was still being explored as a "future business opportunity", according to Chevrolet Vice President Scott Bell.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] In November 2021, Ford Performance released the "Eluminator" 210 kW (281 hp) crate EV motor, which was the same traction motor used in the Ford Mustang Mach-E GT Performance Edition and used to power the 1978 F-100 Eluminator restomod pickup truck.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] As of 3 November 2021, it was available for pre-order but not yet shipping.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] General Motors began developing several small block crate race car engines in 2001 and they were released into production in 2002.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The engines are sealed and repairs being done by certified rebuilders.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The Chevrolet engine debuted in 2002 with part number 1958602 and sold for a little under $4000 in 2012.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It has 350 cubic inch displacement via a 4.000 inch bore and 3.480 inch stroke.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The 602 engine is equipped with iron heads, a cast-iron block, and aluminum pistons.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It produces about 350 horsepower and 390 foot-pounds of torque at 9.1:1 compression.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Applications for this engine include: IMCA Hobby Stock, IMCA Northern Sport Modified, IMCA Southern Sport Modified, Mid-American Stock cars.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Northeastern (United States) Sportman, Crate Racing USA, and others.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The Chevrolet engine has part number 88959603.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It has 355 cubic inch displacement and 405 foot pounds of torque at 10.1:1 compression.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The 603 engine is equipped with aluminum heads, steel crank, and high silicon pistons.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The American Canadian Tour (ACT) late model sportsman utilize this engine.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The Chevrolet engine debuted in 2002 with part number 88958604 and sold for about $5000 in 2012.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] The 604 engine is equipped with aluminum heads, forged steel crankshaft, and an aluminum intake.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] It produces about 400 horsepower and 400 foot-pounds of torque with a 9.6:1 compression.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Applications for this engine includes IMCA Modifieds (starting in 2013), CRA All Stars Tour (allowed but not required), United Crate Racing Alliance, Big 8 Series, RUSH Late Models, Crate Racing USA, and others.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] New castings of some engines are sometimes produced by independent companies.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] These blocks commonly replace rare or popular designs for aftermarket rebuilding, especially when the original is no longer produced.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] They are sometimes available in aluminum instead of original iron, or in stronger alloys.
[src:engine-block/automobile-engine-replacement] Often they imitate the larger available displacements that were produced in small numbers or allow for displacements never available.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:engine-block/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In an internal combustion engine, the **engine block** is the structure that contains the cylinders and other components.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The engine block in an early automotive engine consisted of just the cylinder block, to which a separate crankcase was attached.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Modern engine blocks typically have the crankcase integrated with the cylinder block as a single component.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Engine blocks often also include elements such as coolant passages and oil galleries.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The term "cylinder block" is often used interchangeably with "engine block".
[src:engine-block/engine-block] However, technically, the block of a modern engine (i.e., multiple cylinders integrated with another component) would be classified as a monobloc.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The main structure of an engine typically consists of the cylinders, coolant passages, oil galleries, crankcase, and cylinder head(s).
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The first production engines of the 1880s to 1920s usually used separate components for each element, which were bolted together during engine assembly.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Modern engines, however, often combine many elements into a single component to reduce production costs.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The evolution from separate components to monobloc engine blocks has gradually progressed since the early 20th century.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The integration of elements has relied on the development of foundry and machining techniques.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] For example, a practical, low-cost V8 engine was not feasible until Ford developed the methods used to build its flathead V8 engine.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Other manufacturers then applied those techniques to their engines.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] A cylinder block is a structure that contains the cylinder, plus any cylinder sleeves and coolant passages.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In the earliest decades of internal combustion engine development, monobloc cylinder construction was rare; cylinders were usually cast individually, with separate cylinder blocks produced for each cylinder.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Following that, engines began to combine two or three cylinders into combined cylinder blocks, with engines combining several of these.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In early engines with multiple cylinder banks – such as V6, V8, or flat-6 engines – each bank was typically made of one or multiple separate cylinder blocks.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Since the 1930s, mass production methods have developed to allow both banks of cylinders (as well as the crankcase) to be integrated into the same cylinder block.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Wet liner cylinder blocks use cylinder walls that are entirely removable and fit into the block by means of special gaskets.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] They are called "wet liners" because their outer sides come in direct contact with the engine's coolant.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In other words, the liner is the entire cylinder wall, rather than merely a sleeve.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The advantages of wet liners are lower mass and bulk, and thanks to coolant being heated faster from a cold start, a wet liner engine has lower start-up fuel consumption and can start heating the car cabin sooner.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Wet liner designs are popular with European manufacturers, most notably Renault and Peugeot, who continue to use them to the present.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Dry liner cylinder blocks use either the block's material or a discrete liner inserted into the block to form the backbone of the cylinder wall.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Additional sleeves are inserted within, which remain "dry" outside, surrounded by the block's material.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] For either wet or dry liner designs, the liners (or sleeves) can be replaced, potentially allowing an engine overhaul or rebuild without replacing the block itself.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In reality, however, they are difficult to remove and install, and for most applications (such as most late-model cars and trucks) an engine will never undergo such a procedure in its working lifespan.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] It is likelier to be scrapped, with new equipment—engine or entire vehicle—replacing it.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The crankcase is the structure that houses the crankshaft.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] As with cylinder blocks, this is primarily an integrated component in modern engines.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Engine blocks are typically cast from either cast iron or an aluminium alloy.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Aluminium blocks are much lighter and transfer heat more effectively to coolant, but iron blocks retain some advantages, such as durability and reduced thermal expansion.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In engine blocks made of gray cast iron, weight can be reduced by optimizing the structure and thin-wall casting.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] With this casting technique, a wall thickness of as little as about 3 mm is generally possible.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In comparison, the walls of cast iron engine blocks are usually from 4.0 to 5.5 mm thick.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Using vermicular graphite cast iron (GGV), a casting material with great strength, enables weight reductions by about 30% compared to conventional casting materials such as GG 25.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Weight reduction, to this extent, requires engineering for the engine block, taking into account the particular needs of the material.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] An engine where all the cylinders share a common block is called a monobloc engine.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Most modern engines use a monobloc design, and few have a separate block for each cylinder.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] This has led to the term "engine block," which usually implies a monobloc design, with "monobloc" rarely used.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In the early years of the internal combustion engine, casting technology couldn't produce large castings with complex internal cores (for water jackets etc).
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Most early engines, particularly those with more than four cylinders, had their cylinders cast as pairs or triplets of cylinders, then bolted to a separate crankcase.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] As casting techniques improved, an entire cylinder block of 4, 6, or 8 cylinders could be produced in one piece.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] This monobloc construction was more straightforward and more cost-effective to produce.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] All the cylinders and crankcase could be made in a single component for straight engine cylinder layouts.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] One of the early engines produced using this method is the 4-cylinder engine in the Ford Model T, introduced in 1908.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The technique spread to straight-six engines and was commonly used by the mid-1920s.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Up until the 1930s, most V engines retained a separate block casting for each cylinder bank, with both bolted onto a common crankcase (itself a separate casting).
[src:engine-block/engine-block] For economy, some engines were designed to use identical castings for each bank, left and right.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] A rare exception was the Lancia 22½° narrow-angle V12 of 1919, which used a single block casting combining both banks.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The Ford flathead V8 – introduced in 1932 – represented a significant development in the production of affordable V engines.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] It was the first V8 engine with a single-engine block casting, putting a V8 into an affordable car for the first time.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The communal water jacket of monobloc designs permitted closer spacing between cylinders.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The monobloc design approach also improved engines' torsional rigidity as cylinder numbers, engine lengths, and power ratings increased.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Most engine blocks today, except some unusual V or radial engines and large marine engines, use a monobloc design with one block for all cylinders plus an integrated crankcase.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] In such cases, the skirts of the cylinder banks form a crankcase area of sorts, which is still often called a crankcase despite no longer being a discrete part.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Using steel cylinder liners and bearing shells minimizes the effect of the relative softness of aluminium.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Some engine designs use plasma transferred wire arc thermal spraying, instead of cylinder sleeves, to further reduce weight.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] These types of engines can also be made of compacted graphite iron, such as in some diesel engines.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Some modern consumer-grade small engines use a monobloc design where the cylinder head, block, and half of the crankcase share the same casting.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Apart from cost, one reason for this is to produce an overall lower engine height.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] The primary disadvantage can be that repairs become more time-consuming and impractical.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] An example of engines with integrated cylinder heads are the Honda GC-series and GXV-series engines, which are sometimes called "Uniblock" by Honda.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Several cars with transverse engines have used an engine block consisting of an integrated transmission and crankcase.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Cars that have used this arrangement include the 1966-1973 Lamborghini Miura and cars using the BMC A-series and E-series engines.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] This design often results in the engine and transmission sharing the same oil.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Motorcycles such as the Honda CB750 use a similar layout, with the cylinder block and crankcase integrated with part of the transmission.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] Many farm tractor designs integrate the cylinder block, crankcase, transmission, and rear axle into a single unit.
[src:engine-block/engine-block] An early example is the Fordson tractor.
